<div id="sacred" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">01</span>The sacred and the profane</h2>
  <p>Eliade's organizing word is <em>hierophany</em>: a showing-through of the sacred into ordinary things. A stone, a tree, a doorway, a river — and suddenly the thing is more than the thing, without ceasing to be the thing. He argued that for most people in most of history, the world was not flat and uniform. It was charged. Some places and times were dense with meaning; others were not. The sacred and the profane were two ways the same world could be experienced.</p>
  <p>Modernity, in his account, is what happens when the charge is declared an illusion — when every stone is only a stone, every place interchangeable with every other, every moment the same empty unit of clock-time. He did not think this made modern people free of the sacred. He thought it drove the sacred underground, into forms the disenchanted no longer recognize as religious at all.</p>
</div>
<div id="return" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">02</span>The eternal return</h2>
  <p>Profane time is a line: one thing after another, none of it repeating, all of it running out. Sacred time, Eliade argued, is different in kind. A ritual does not merely <em>remember</em> a first morning of the world; it returns the participant to it, makes that founding time present again. He called the founding time <em>illud tempus</em> — "that time," the time of beginnings. <em>The Myth of the Eternal Return</em> (1954 in English) is his case that archaic cultures organized life around this recovery: the new year, the planted field, the built house all re-enacted a creation, refusing the pure line of history.</p>
  <p>He was honest that this was, in part, a refusal of history's terror — a way of making suffering bearable by referring it to a pattern larger than the sufferer. The disenchanted have lost that container. Whether what replaced it is freedom or exposure is exactly the question the rest of this site is asking.</p>
</div>
<div id="ecstasy" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">03</span>Archaic techniques of ecstasy</h2>
  <p>Eliade's study of shamanism carried a precise subtitle: <em>archaic techniques of ecstasy</em>. Across cultures that had never met, he traced a recurring structure — the practitioner undergoes an initiatory death, a descent and dismemberment, and returns able to do for others what they could not do before. The descent was not a breakdown. It was a curriculum, and every old culture built a <em>container</em> for it.</p>
  <div class="callout"><span class="callout-label">A parallel in this book</span><p>This is the structure Bill Plotkin walks people into and back from — what he calls the descent to soul. Eliade is the scholar of the same passage Plotkin is the practitioner of: he documented, across the archaic cultures he studied, the very initiation our own has, in the book's words, "forgotten how to hold." Where Plotkin maps the descent from the inside, Eliade catalogued the containers — and his catalogue is evidence that the container is not exotic. It is human, and it is recoverable.</p></div>
</div>
<div id="reckoning" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">04</span>The reckoning</h2>
  <p>None of this can be read clean. In the late 1930s Eliade lent his prestige to the Iron Guard — Romania's fascist, antisemitic Legionary movement — writing articles for its press that praised it as "a Christian revolution aimed at creating a new Romania," and enrolling in its political wing. In 1938, when King Carol II turned on the Guard, Eliade was imprisoned, and he refused to sign a declaration dissociating himself from it. During the war he served the Romanian regimes as a cultural attaché; in 1942 he published a book admiring Salazar's "Christian and totalitarian" Estado Novo. After the war he did not confront this record. He let it stay quiet, and built his great scholarly career on the far side of a silence.</p>
  <p>The picture is not simple, and the simple versions in both directions are wrong. He had signed an anti-Nazi-racism statement in 1933 and deplored the expulsion of Jewish scholars in 1936; defenders note he never wrote the crude antisemitic propaganda some Guardists did. None of that dissolves it. A thinker who understood, better than almost anyone, how the sacred can seize a whole people and move them as one — chose a movement that wielded exactly that power, and it murdered. The non-confrontation afterward is its own fact. We do not place him here despite this. We place him with it.</p>
</div>
<div id="terrain" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">05</span>The sacred is a terrain</h2>
  <p>That contradiction is not a reason to discard Eliade. It is the reason he belongs. This book's core move is that every tool of power is two-faced: the same spell encloses or commons, depending on who casts it and toward what. The sacred is the clearest case. Re-enchantment — feeling the charge come back into the world, the connections that were always there — is one casting. Blood-and-soil fascism, the nation made holy and the outsider made profane, is the other. Eliade's scholarship gives us the first. Eliade's life is the warning about the second.</p>
  <div class="callout"><span class="callout-label">For the commons</span><p>Take the structure, hold the warning. The disenchantment of the world was an enclosure — of the sacred, and of the human capacity to perceive it. Eliade is the strongest witness that the enchanted world was real and structured, not superstition to be outgrown. The work of re-enchantment is to feel that charge again — and the discipline that separates it from its fascist twin is the commons itself: the sacred held in common, entered by many doors, never fused into one people's claim on the holy.</p></div>
</div>
